# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acetogenesis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] All acetic acid bacteria are rod-shaped and obligate aerobes.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] Acetic acid bacteria are airborne and are ubiquitous in nature.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] They are actively present in environments where ethanol is being formed as a product of the fermentation of sugars.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] They can be isolated from the nectar of flowers and from damaged fruit.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] Other good sources are fresh apple cider and unpasteurized beer that has not been filter sterilized.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] In these liquids, they grow as a surface film due to their aerobic nature and active motility.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] Fruit flies or vinegar eels are considered common vectors in the propagation of acetic acid bacteria.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] The growth of *Acetobacter* in wine can be suppressed through effective sanitation, by complete exclusion of air from wine in storage, and by the use of moderate amounts of sulfur dioxide in the wine as a preservative.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] Vinegar is produced when acetic acid bacteria act on alcoholic beverages such as wine.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] Specific oxidation reactions occur through oxidative fermentation, which creates vinegar as a byproduct.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] In the biotechnological industry, these bacteria's oxidation mechanism is exploited to produce a number of compounds such as l-ascorbic acid, dihydroxyacetone, gluconic acid, and cellulose.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] Besides food industry, some acetic acid bacteria are used as biocatalysts for the industrial production of compounds.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] They are used as the important biocatalysts for the development of eco-friendly fermentation processes as an alternative to the chemical synthesis.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] Some genera, such as *Acetobacter*, can oxidize ethanol to carbon dioxide and water using Krebs cycle enzymes.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] Other genera, such as *Gluconobacter*, do not oxidize ethanol, as they do not have a full set of Krebs cycle enzymes.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] As these bacteria produce acid, they are usually acid-tolerant, growing well below pH 5.0, although the pH optimum for growth is 5.4-6.3.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid-bacteria] *Acetobacter xylinum* is able to synthesize cellulose, something normally done only by plants.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is the second simplest carboxylic acid (after formic acid).
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] It is an important chemical reagent and industrial chemical across various fields, used primarily in the production of cellulose acetate for photographic film, polyvinyl acetate for wood glue, and synthetic fibres and fabrics.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In households, diluted acetic acid is often used in descaling agents.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In the food industry, acetic acid is controlled by the food additive code E260 as an acidity regulator and as a condiment.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In biochemistry, the acetyl group, derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] When bound to coenzyme A, it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The global demand for acetic acid as of 2023 is about 17.88 million metric tonnes per year (t/a).
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Most of the world's acetic acid is produced via the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Its production and subsequent industrial use poses health hazards to workers, including incidental skin damage and chronic respiratory injuries from inhalation.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The trivial name "acetic acid" is the most commonly used and preferred IUPAC name.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The systematic name "ethanoic acid", a valid IUPAC name, is constructed according to the substitutive nomenclature.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The name "acetic acid" derives from the Latin word for vinegar, "*acetum*", which means "to sour" in relation to the bitter taste of fermented fruits.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] "Glacial acetic acid" is a name for water-free (anhydrous) acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Similar to the German name "Eisessig" ("ice vinegar"), the name comes from the solid ice-like crystals that form with agitation, slightly below room temperature at 16.6 °C (61.9 °F).
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can never be truly water-free in an atmosphere that contains water, so the presence of 0.1% water in glacial acetic acid lowers its melting point by 0.2 °C.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] A common symbol for acetic acid is AcOH (or HOAc), where Ac is the pseudoelement symbol representing the acetyl group CH3−C(=O)−; the conjugate base, acetate (CH3COO−), is thus represented as AcO−.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetate is the ion resulting from loss of H+ from acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The name "acetate" can also refer to a salt containing this anion, or an ester of acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] (The symbol Ac for the acetyl functional group is not to be confused with the symbol Ac for the element actinium; context prevents confusion among organic chemists).
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] To better reflect its structure, acetic acid is often written as CH3−C(O)OH, CH3−C(=O)−OH, CH3COOH, and CH3CO2H.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In the context of acid–base reactions, the abbreviation HAc is sometimes used, where Ac in this case is a symbol for acetate (rather than acetyl).
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The carboxymethyl functional group derived from removing one hydrogen from the methyl group of acetic acid has the chemical formula −CH2−C(=O)−OH.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic acid, the dilute solution of which is known as vinegar, is likely the first acid to be produced in large quantities in history.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Vinegar has been used for at least 10,000 years as it is the natural result of exposure of beer and wine to air because acetic acid-producing bacteria are present globally.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Hippocrates used vinegar as an antiseptic and as a remedy for numerous conditions including fever, constipation, ulcers, and pleurisy.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Ancient Romans boiled soured wine to produce a highly sweet syrup called *sapa*.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Sapa that was produced in lead pots was rich in lead acetate, a sweet substance also called *sugar of lead* or *sugar of Saturn*, which contributed to lead poisoning among the Roman aristocracy.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In the 16th-century German alchemist Andreas Libavius described the production of acetone from the dry distillation of lead acetate, ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The presence of water in vinegar has such a profound effect on acetic acid's properties that for centuries chemists believed that glacial acetic acid and the acid found in vinegar were two different substances.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] French chemist Pierre Adet proved them identical.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In 1845 German chemist Hermann Kolbe synthesized acetic acid from inorganic compounds for the first time.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] This reaction sequence consisted of chlorination of carbon disulfide to carbon tetrachloride, followed by pyrolysis to tetrachloroethylene and aqueous chlorination to trichloroacetic acid, and concluded with electrolytic reduction to acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] By 1910, most glacial acetic acid was obtained from pyroligneous liquor, a product of the destructive distillation of wood.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The acetic acid was isolated by treatment with milk of lime, and the resulting calcium acetate was then acidified with sulfuric acid to recover acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] At that time, Germany was producing 10,000 tons of glacial acetic acid, around 30% of which was used for the manufacture of indigo dye.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Because both methanol and carbon monoxide are commodity raw materials, methanol carbonylation long appeared to be an attractive method of acetic acid production.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Henri Dreyfus at British Celanese developed a methanol carbonylation pilot plant as early as 1925.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] However, a lack of practical materials that could contain the corrosive reaction mixture at the high pressures needed (200 atm or more) discouraged commercialization of these routes.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The first commercial methanol carbonylation process, which used a cobalt catalyst, was developed by German chemical company BASF in 1963.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In 1968, a rhodium-based catalyst (*cis*−[Rh(CO)2I2]−) was discovered that could operate efficiently at lower pressure with almost no by-products.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] US chemical company Monsanto Company built the first plant using this catalyst in 1970, and rhodium-catalyzed methanol carbonylation became the dominant method of acetic acid production (see Monsanto process).
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In the late 1990s, BP Chemicals commercialized the Cativa catalyst ([Ir(CO)2I2]−), which is promoted by iridium for greater efficiency.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Known as the Cativa process, the iridium-catalyzed production of glacial acetic acid is greener, and has largely supplanted the Monsanto process, often in the same production plants.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Interstellar acetic acid was first detected in the Sagittarius B2 North molecular cloud (also known as the Sgr B2 Large Molecule Heimat source).
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Because of this release of the proton (H+), acetic acid has acidic character.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In aqueous solution, it has a pKa value of 4.76.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Its conjugate base is acetate (CH3COO−).
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] A 1.0 M solution (about the concentration of domestic vinegar) has a pH of 2.4, indicating that merely 0.4% of the acetic acid molecules are ionized.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In solid acetic acid, the molecules form chains of individual molecules interconnected by hydrogen bonds.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In the vapour phase at 120 °C (248 °F), dimers can be detected.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Dimers also occur in the liquid phase in dilute solutions with non-hydrogen-bonding solvents, and to a certain extent in pure acetic acid, but are disrupted by hydrogen-bonding solvents.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The dissociation enthalpy of the dimer is estimated at 65.0–66.0 kJ/mol, and the dissociation entropy at 154–157 J mol−1 K−1.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Other carboxylic acids engage in similar intermolecular hydrogen bonding interactions.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Liquid acetic acid is a hydrophilic (polar) protic solvent, similar to ethanol and water.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] With a relative static permittivity (dielectric constant) of 6.2, it dissolves not only polar compounds such as inorganic salts and sugars, but also non-polar compounds such as oils as well as polar solutes.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] It is miscible with polar and non-polar solvents such as water, chloroform, and hexane.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] With higher alkanes (starting with octane), acetic acid is not miscible at all compositions, and solubility of acetic acid in alkanes declines with longer n-alkanes.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The solvent and miscibility properties of acetic acid make it a useful industrial chemical, for example, as a solvent in the production of dimethyl terephthalate.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] At physiological pHs, acetic acid is usually fully ionized to acetate in aqueous solution.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The acetyl group, formally derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Typically, it is bound to coenzyme A by acetyl-CoA synthetase enzymes, where it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Unlike longer-chain carboxylic acids (the fatty acids), acetic acid does not occur in natural triglycerides.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Most of the acetate generated in cells for use in acetyl-CoA is synthesized directly from ethanol or pyruvate.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] However, the artificial triglyceride triacetin (glycerine triacetate) is a common food additive and is found in cosmetics and topical medicines; this additive is metabolized to glycerol and acetic acid in the body.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced and excreted by acetic acid bacteria, notably the genus *Acetobacter* and *Clostridium acetobutylicum*.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] These bacteria are found universally in foodstuffs, water, and soil, and acetic acid is produced naturally as fruits and other foods spoil.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is also a component of the vaginal lubrication of humans and other primates, where it appears to serve as a mild antibacterial agent.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced industrially both naturally via bacterial fermentation and synthetically.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] About 75% of acetic acid made for use in the chemical industry is made by the carbonylation of methanol, explained below.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The biological route accounts for only about 10% of world production, but it remains important for the production of vinegar because many food purity laws require vinegar used in foods to be of biological origin.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Other processes are methyl formate isomerization, conversion of syngas to acetic acid, and gas phase oxidation of ethylene and ethanol.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can be purified via fractional freezing using an ice bath.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The water and other impurities will remain liquid while the acetic acid will precipitate out.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] As of 2003–2005, total worldwide production of virgin acetic acid was estimated at 5 Mt/a (million tonnes per year), approximately half of which was produced in the United States.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] European production was approximately 1 Mt/a and declining, while Japanese production was 0.7 Mt/a.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Another 1.5 Mt were recycled each year, bringing the total world market to 6.5 Mt/a.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Since then, the global production has increased from 10.7 Mt/a in 2010 to 17.88 Mt/a in 2023.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The two biggest producers of virgin acetic acid are Celanese and BP Chemicals.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Other major producers include Millennium Chemicals, Sterling Chemicals, Samsung, Eastman, and Svensk Etanolkemi.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Most acetic acid is produced by methanol carbonylation.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The process involves iodomethane as an intermediate, and occurs in three steps.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] A metal carbonyl catalyst is needed for the carbonylation (step 2).
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Two related processes exist for the carbonylation of methanol: the rhodium-catalyzed Monsanto process, and the iridium-catalyzed Cativa process.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The latter process is greener and more efficient and has largely supplanted the former process.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Catalytic amounts of water are used in both processes, but the Cativa process requires less, so the water-gas shift reaction is suppressed, and fewer by-products are formed.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] By altering the process conditions, acetic anhydride may also be produced in plants using rhodium catalysis.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Prior to the commercialization of the Monsanto process, most acetic acid was produced by oxidation of acetaldehyde.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] This remains the second-most-important manufacturing method, although it is usually not competitive with the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The acetaldehyde can be produced by hydration of acetylene.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] This was the dominant technology in the early 1900s.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Such oxidations require metal catalyst, such as the naphthenate salts of manganese, cobalt, and chromium.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The typical reaction is conducted at temperatures and pressures designed to be as hot as possible while still keeping the butane a liquid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Typical reaction conditions are 150 °C (302 °F) and 55 atm.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Side-products may also form, including butanone, ethyl acetate, formic acid, and propionic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] These side-products are also commercially valuable, and the reaction conditions may be altered to produce more of them where needed.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] However, the separation of acetic acid from these by-products adds to the cost of the process.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Similar conditions and catalysts are used for butane oxidation, the oxygen in air to produce acetic acid can oxidize acetaldehyde.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Using modern catalysts, this reaction can have an acetic acid yield greater than 95%.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The major side-products are ethyl acetate, formic acid, and formaldehyde, all of which have lower boiling points than acetic acid and are readily separated by distillation.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetaldehyde may be prepared from ethylene via the Wacker process, and then oxidized as above.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In more recent times, chemical company Showa Denko, which opened an ethylene oxidation plant in Ōita, Japan, in 1997, commercialized a cheaper single-stage conversion of ethylene to acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The process is catalyzed by a palladium metal catalyst supported on a heteropoly acid such as silicotungstic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] It is thought to be competitive with methanol carbonylation for smaller plants (100–250 kt/a), depending on the local price of ethylene.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] For most of human history, acetic acid bacteria of the genus *Acetobacter* have made acetic acid, in the form of vinegar.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Given sufficient oxygen, these bacteria can produce vinegar from a variety of alcoholic foodstuffs.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Commonly used feeds include apple cider, wine, and fermented grain, malt, rice, or potato mashes.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] A dilute alcohol solution inoculated with *Acetobacter* and kept in a warm, airy place will become vinegar over the course of a few months.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Industrial vinegar-making methods accelerate this process by improving the supply of oxygen to the bacteria.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The first batches of vinegar produced by fermentation probably followed errors in the winemaking process.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] If must is fermented at too high a temperature, acetobacter will overwhelm the yeast naturally occurring on the grapes.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] As the demand for vinegar for culinary, medical, and sanitary purposes increased, vintners quickly learned to use other organic materials to produce vinegar in the hot summer months before the grapes were ripe and ready for processing into wine.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] This method was slow, however, and not always successful, as the vintners did not understand the process.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] One of the first modern commercial processes was the "fast method" or "German method", first practised in Germany in 1823.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In this process, fermentation takes place in a tower packed with wood shavings or charcoal.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The alcohol-containing feed is trickled into the top of the tower, and fresh air supplied from the bottom by either natural or forced convection.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The improved air supply in this process cut the time to prepare vinegar from months to weeks.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Nowadays, most vinegar is made in submerged tank culture, first described in 1949 by Otto Hromatka and Heinrich Ebner.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In this method, alcohol is fermented to vinegar in a continuously stirred tank, and oxygen is supplied by bubbling air through the solution.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Using modern applications of this method, vinegar of 15% acetic acid can be prepared in only 24 hours in batch process, even 20% in 60-hour fed-batch process.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Species of anaerobic bacteria, including members of the genus *Clostridium* or *Acetobacterium*, can convert sugars to acetic acid directly without creating ethanol as an intermediate.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] This ability of *Clostridium* to metabolize sugars directly, or to produce acetic acid from less costly inputs, suggests that these bacteria could produce acetic acid more efficiently than ethanol-oxidizers like *Acetobacter*.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] However, *Clostridium* bacteria are less acid-tolerant than *Acetobacter*.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Even the most acid-tolerant *Clostridium* strains can produce vinegar in concentrations of only a few percent, compared to *Acetobacter* strains that can produce vinegar in concentrations up to 20%.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] At present, it remains more cost-effective to produce vinegar using *Acetobacter*, rather than using *Clostridium* and concentrating it.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] As a result, although acetogenic bacteria have been known since 1940, their industrial use is confined to a few niche applications.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is a chemical reagent for the production of chemical compounds.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The largest single use of acetic acid is in the production of vinyl acetate monomer, closely followed by acetic anhydride and ester production.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The volume of acetic acid used in vinegar is comparatively small.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The primary use of acetic acid is the production of vinyl acetate monomer (VAM).
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In 2008, this application was estimated to consume a third of the world's production of acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The reaction consists of ethylene and acetic acid with oxygen over a palladium catalyst, conducted in the gas phase.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Vinyl acetate can be polymerized to polyvinyl acetate or other polymers, which are components in paints and adhesives.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The major esters of acetic acid are commonly used as solvents for inks, paints and coatings.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The esters include ethyl acetate, *n*-butyl acetate, isobutyl acetate, and propyl acetate.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] For example, acetic acid and ethanol gives ethyl acetate and water.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Most acetate esters, however, are produced from acetaldehyde using the Tishchenko reaction.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In addition, ether acetates are used as solvents for nitrocellulose, acrylic lacquers, varnish removers, and wood stains.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] First, glycol monoethers are produced from ethylene oxide or propylene oxide with alcohol, which are then esterified with acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The three major products are ethylene glycol monoethyl ether acetate (EEA), ethylene glycol monobutyl ether acetate (EBA), and propylene glycol monomethyl ether acetate (PMA, more commonly known as PGMEA in semiconductor manufacturing processes, where it is used as a resist solvent).
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] This application consumes about 15% to 20% of worldwide acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Ether acetates, for example EEA, have been shown to be harmful to human reproduction.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The product of the condensation of two molecules of acetic acid is acetic anhydride.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The worldwide production of acetic anhydride is a major application, and uses approximately 25% to 30% of the global production of acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The main process involves dehydration of acetic acid to give ketene at 700–750 °C.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is an acetylation agent.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] As such, its major application is for cellulose acetate, a synthetic textile also used for photographic film, which is produced by reacting cellulose with acetic acid and acetic anhydride in the presence of sulfuric acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is also a reagent for the production of heroin and other compounds.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] As a polar protic solvent, acetic acid is frequently used for recrystallization to purify organic compounds.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as a solvent in the production of terephthalic acid (TPA), the raw material for polyethylene terephthalate (PET).
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In 2006, about 20% of acetic acid was used for TPA production.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is often used as a solvent for reactions involving carbocations, such as Friedel-Crafts alkylation.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] For example, one stage in the commercial manufacture of synthetic camphor involves a Wagner-Meerwein rearrangement of camphene to isobornyl acetate; here acetic acid acts both as a solvent and as a nucleophile to trap the rearranged carbocation.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is used in analytical chemistry for the estimation of weakly alkaline substances such as organic amides.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is a much weaker base than water, so the amide behaves as a strong base in this medium.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] It then can be titrated using a solution in glacial acetic acid of a very strong acid, such as perchloric acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic acid injection into a tumor has been used to treat cancer since the 1800s.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as part of cervical cancer screening in many areas in the developing world.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The acid is applied to the cervix and if an area of white appears after about a minute the test is positive.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is an effective antiseptic when used as a 1% solution, with broad spectrum of activity against streptococci, staphylococci, pseudomonas, enterococci and others.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] It may be used to treat skin infections caused by pseudomonas strains resistant to typical antibiotics.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] While diluted acetic acid is used in iontophoresis, no high quality evidence supports this treatment for rotator cuff disease.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] As a treatment for otitis externa, it is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Vinegar is typically no less than 4% acetic acid by mass.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Legal limits on acetic acid content vary by jurisdiction.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Vinegar is used directly as a condiment, and in the pickling of vegetables and other foods.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Table vinegar tends to be more diluted (4% to 8% acetic acid), while commercial food pickling employs solutions that are more concentrated.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The proportion of acetic acid used worldwide as vinegar is not as large as industrial uses, but it is by far the oldest and best-known application.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetic acid undergoes the typical chemical reactions of a carboxylic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Upon treatment with a standard base, it converts to metal acetate and water.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] With strong bases (e.g., organolithium reagents), it can be doubly deprotonated to give LiCH2COOLi.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The OH group is the main site of reaction, as illustrated by the conversion of acetic acid to acetyl chloride.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Other substitution derivatives include acetic anhydride; this anhydride is produced by loss of water from two molecules of acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Esters of acetic acid can likewise be formed via Fischer esterification, and amides can be formed.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Because aluminium forms a passivating acid-resistant film of aluminium oxide, aluminium tanks are used to transport acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Containers lined with glass, stainless steel or polyethylene are also used for this purpose.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] A colour reaction for salts of acetic acid is iron(III) chloride solution, which results in a deeply red colour that disappears after acidification.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] A more sensitive test uses lanthanum nitrate with iodine and ammonia to give a blue solution.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Acetates when heated with arsenic trioxide form cacodyl oxide, which can be detected by its malodorous vapours.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Organic or inorganic salts are produced from acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Halogenated acetic acids are produced from acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Amounts of acetic acid used in these other applications together account for another 5–10% of acetic acid use worldwide.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Prolonged inhalation exposure (eight hours) to acetic acid vapours at 10 ppm can produce some irritation of eyes, nose, and throat; at 100 ppm marked lung irritation and possible damage to lungs, eyes, and skin may result.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Vapour concentrations of 1,000 ppm cause marked irritation of eyes, nose and upper respiratory tract and cannot be tolerated.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] These predictions were based on animal experiments and industrial exposure.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] In 12 workers exposed for two or more years to an airborne average concentration of 51 ppm acetic acid (estimated), symptoms of conjunctive irritation, upper respiratory tract irritation, and hyperkeratotic dermatitis were produced.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Exposure to 50 ppm or more is intolerable to most persons and results in intensive lacrimation and irritation of the eyes, nose, and throat, with pharyngeal oedema and chronic bronchitis.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Unacclimatized humans experience extreme eye and nasal irritation at concentrations in excess of 25 ppm, and conjunctivitis from concentrations below 10 ppm has been reported.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid (≥ 25%) is corrosive to skin.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] These burns or blisters may not appear until hours after exposure.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] The hazardous properties of acetic acid are dependent on the concentration of the (typically aqueous) solution, with the most significant increases in hazard levels at thresholds of 25% and 90% acetic acid concentration by weight.
[src:acetogenesis/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid can be ignited only with difficulty at standard temperature and pressure, but becomes a flammable risk in temperatures greater than 39 °C (102 °F), and can form explosive mixtures with air at increased temperatures with explosive limits of 5.4–16% concentration.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] An **acetogen** is a microorganism that generates acetate (CH3COO−) as an end product of either anaerobic respiration or fermentation.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] This process is known as acetogenesis, and is different from acetate fermentation, although both occur in the absence of molecular oxygen (O2) and produce acetate.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] Although previously thought that only bacteria are acetogens, some archaea can be considered to be acetogens.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] Acetogens are found in a variety of habitats, generally those that are anaerobic (lack oxygen).
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] Acetogens can use a variety of compounds as sources of energy and carbon; the best studied form of acetogenic metabolism involves the use of carbon dioxide as a carbon source and hydrogen as an energy source.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] Carbon dioxide reduction is carried out by the key enzyme acetyl-CoA synthase.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] Together with methane-forming archaea, acetogens constitute the last limbs in the anaerobic food web that leads to the production of methane from polymers in the absence of oxygen.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] Acetogens may represent ancestors of the first bioenergetically active cells in evolution.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] Acetogens have diverse metabolic roles, which help them thrive in different environments.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] One of their metabolic products is acetate which is an important nutrient for the host and its inhabiting microbial community, most seen in termite's guts.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] Acetogens also serve as "hydrogen sinks" in termite's GI tract.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] Hydrogen gas inhibits biodegradation and acetogens use up these hydrogen gases in the anaerobic environment to favor the biodegradative capacity of the host by reacting hydrogen gas and carbon dioxide to make acetate.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] Acetogens have the ability to use variety of substrates in an event where another competitor such as a methanogen makes hydrogen gas a limiting substrate.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] Acetogens can use and convert alcohols, lactates and fatty acids, which are usually restricted to syntrophs, instead of just carbon dioxide and hydrogen.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] This enables them to take on the roles of important contributors of food chain such as primary fermenters.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] Acetogens can work together with methanogens, as exemplified by the conversion of carbohydrates by a Methanosarcina barkeri and coculture of A. woodii.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] The methanogen takes up acetate to favor the acetogen.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] Sometimes the interspecies transfer of hydrogen gas between A. woodii and an H2-consuming methanogen results in hydrogen gas being released from the acetogen instead of going toward acetogenesis by the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] Acetogens are also one of the contributors to corrosion of steel.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogen] Acetobacterium woodii utilize hydrogen gas and CO2 to make the acetate that is used as carbon source for many of the sulfate-reducing bacteria growing with hydrogen gas and sulfate.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] Reduction of CO2 to acetic acid via the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway requires an electron source (e.g., H2, CO, formate, etc.).
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] When acetogens are grown autotrophically, they synthesize acetic acid only through the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway; but when they are grown heterotrophically, they can produce additional acetic acid by oxidation of the carbon source (carbohydrates, organic acids, or alcohols).
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] Once produced, acetyl-CoA can be incorporated into biomass or converted to acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] In 1932, organisms were discovered that could convert hydrogen gas and carbon dioxide into acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] The first acetogenic bacterium species, *Clostridium aceticum*, was discovered in 1936 by Klaas Tammo Wieringa.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] A second species, *Moorella thermoacetica*, attracted wide interest because of its ability, reported in 1942, to convert glucose into three moles of acetic acid, a process called homoacetate fermentation.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] The precursor to acetic acid is the thioester acetyl CoA.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] The key aspects of the acetogenic pathway are several reactions that include the reduction of carbon dioxide (CO2) to carbon monoxide (CO) and the attachment of CO to a methyl group (–CH3) and coenzyme A.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] The first process is catalyzed by enzymes called carbon monoxide dehydrogenase.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] The coupling of the methyl group (provided by methylcobalamin), the CO, and the coenzyme A is catalyzed by acetyl-CoA synthase.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] However, what matters for the cell is how much ATP is generated.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] The unique metabolism of acetogens has significance in biotechnological uses.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] In carbohydrate fermentations, the decarboxylation reactions end in the conversion of organic carbon into carbon dioxide.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] In the production of biofuels, the need to reduce CO2 emissions, as well as the need to be competitive, means that this inefficiency should perhaps be eliminated by using acetogens.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] Acetogenesis does not replace glycolysis with a different pathway but rather captures the CO2 from glycolysis and uses it to produce acetic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetogenesis] Although three molecules of acetic acid can be produced in this way, production of three molecules of ethanol would require an additional reducing agent such as hydrogen gas.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Coenzyme A (CoASH or CoA) consists of a β-mercaptoethylamine group linked to pantothenic acid (vitamin B5) through an amide linkage and 3'-phosphorylated ADP.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] The acetyl group (indicated in blue in the structural diagram on the right) of acetyl-CoA is linked to the sulfhydryl substituent of the β-mercaptoethylamine group.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] This thioester linkage is a "high energy" bond, which is particularly reactive.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Hydrolysis of the thioester bond is exergonic (−31.5 kJ/mol).
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] CoA is acetylated to acetyl-CoA by the breakdown of carbohydrates through glycolysis and by the breakdown of fatty acids through β-oxidation.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA then enters the citric acid cycle, where the acetyl group is oxidized to carbon dioxide and water, and the energy released is captured in the form of 11 ATP and one GTP per acetyl group.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Konrad Bloch and Feodor Lynen were awarded the 1964 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discoveries linking acetyl-CoA and fatty acid metabolism.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Fritz Lipmann won the Nobel Prize in 1953 for his discovery of the cofactor coenzyme A.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is a metabolic intermediate that is involved in many metabolic pathways in an organism.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] It is produced during the breakdown of glucose, fatty acids, and amino acids, and is used in the synthesis of many other biomolecules, including cholesterol, fatty acids, and ketone bodies.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is also a key molecule in the citric acid cycle, which is a series of chemical reactions that occur in the mitochondria of cells and is responsible for generating energy in the form of ATP.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] In addition, acetyl-CoA is a precursor for the biosynthesis of various acetyl-chemicals, acting as an intermediate to transfer an acetyl group during the biosynthesis of those acetyl-chemicals.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is also involved in the regulation of various cellular mechanisms by providing acetyl groups to target amino acid residues for post-translational acetylation reactions of proteins.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] The acetylation of CoA is determined by the carbon sources.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] At high glucose levels, glycolysis takes place rapidly, thus increasing the amount of citrate produced from the citric acid cycle.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] This citrate is then exported to other organelles outside the mitochondria to be broken into acetyl-CoA and oxaloacetate by the enzyme ATP citrate lyase (ACL).
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] This principal reaction is coupled with the hydrolysis of ATP.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] At low glucose levels CoA is acetylated using acetate by acetyl-CoA synthetase (ACS), also coupled with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Ethanol also serves as a carbon source for acetylation of CoA utilizing the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Degradation of branched-chain ketogenic amino acids such as valine, leucine, and isoleucine occurs.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] These amino acids are converted to α-ketoacids by transamination and eventually to isovaleryl-CoA through oxidative decarboxylation by an α-ketoacid dehydrogenase complex.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Isovaleryl-CoA undergoes dehydrogenation, carboxylation and hydration to form another CoA-derivative intermediate before it is cleaved into acetyl-CoA and acetoacetate.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Additionally, malonyl-CoA decarboxylase (MCD), present in the cytosol, contributes to the extramitochondrial acetyl-CoA pool by converting malonyl-CoA into acetyl-CoA.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] At high glucose levels, acetyl-CoA is produced through glycolysis.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Pyruvate undergoes oxidative decarboxylation in which it loses its carboxyl group (as carbon dioxide) to form acetyl-CoA, giving off 33.5 kJ/mol of energy.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] The oxidative conversion of pyruvate into acetyl-CoA is referred to as the **pyruvate dehydrogenase reaction**.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] It is catalyzed by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Other conversions between pyruvate and acetyl-CoA are possible.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] For example, pyruvate formate lyase disproportionates pyruvate into acetyl-CoA and formic acid.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] At low glucose levels, the production of acetyl-CoA is linked to β-oxidation of fatty acids.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Fatty acids are first converted to acyl-CoA.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Acyl-CoA is then degraded in a four-step cycle of oxidation, hydration, oxidation and thiolysis catalyzed by four respective enzymes, namely acyl-CoA dehydrogenase, enoyl-CoA hydratase, 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase, and thiolase.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] The cycle produces a new fatty acid chain with two fewer carbons and acetyl-CoA as a byproduct.
[src:acetogenesis/acetyl-coa] Within mitochondria, MCD similarly facilitates acetyl-CoA production by decarboxylating malonyl-CoA, thereby supporting metabolic flexibility during low-glucose states.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] An **anaerobic organism** or **anaerobe** is any organism that does not require molecular oxygen for its growth.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] It may react negatively or even die in the presence of free oxygen.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Anaerobic organisms do not use oxygen as a terminal electron acceptor in their respiration process to produce energy, but a less powerful oxidizing agent, such as nitrate, ferric ion, Mn(IV), sulfate or bicarbonate anions.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] In contrast, an aerobic organism (aerobe) is an organism that requires a sufficiently oxygenated environment to respire, produce its energy, and thrive.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] However, a minuscule multicellular organism, with an exceptionally rare metabolism and surviving in a hypersaline brine pool in the darkness of the bottom of the Mediterranean Sea, has been recently discovered.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Meanwhile, it remains a scientific curiosity, as the much higher energy requirements of most multicellular organisms cannot be met by anaerobic respiration.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] The deep seafloor and its underlying unconsolidated sediments ranks among the largest potential habitats for anaerobic microorganisms on Earth.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Moreover, chemoautotroph microbes also thrive around hydrothermal vents, discharging hot water on the ocean seabed near mid-ocean ridges, where anaerobic conditions prevail.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] These microbes produce energy in the absence of sunlight or oxygen through a process called anaerobic respiration, whereby inorganic compounds and ions such as protons (H+), elemental sulfur and its derivatives (SO2−4, S2O2−3), or ferric ions, are reduced to drive oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] In his 14 June 1680 letter to the Royal Society, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek described an experiment he carried out by filling two identical glass tubes about halfway with crushed pepper powder, to which some clean rain water was added.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Van Leeuwenhoek sealed one of the glass tubes with a flame and left the other open.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] In 1913, Martinus Beijerinck repeated Van Leeuwenhoek's experiment and identified *Clostridium butyricum* as a prominent anaerobic bacterium in the sealed pepper infusion tube liquid.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Some obligate anaerobes use fermentation, while others use anaerobic respiration.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Aerotolerant organisms are strictly fermentative.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] In the presence of oxygen, facultative anaerobes use aerobic respiration.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] In the absence of oxygen, some facultative anaerobes use fermentation, while others may use anaerobic respiration.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] There are many anaerobic fermentative reactions.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] The energy released in this reaction (without ADP and phosphate) is approximately 150 kJ per mol, which is conserved in generating two ATP from ADP per glucose.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] This is only 5% of the energy per sugar molecule that the typical aerobic reaction generates.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] The energy released is about 180 kJ/mol, which is conserved when 2 ATP are generated from 2 ADP per glucose.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Anaerobic bacteria and archaea use these and many other fermentative pathways, e.g., propionic acid fermentation, butyric acid fermentation, solvent fermentation, mixed acid fermentation, butanediol fermentation, Stickland fermentation, acetogenesis, or methanogenesis.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Creatine, an organic compound found in animals, provides a way for ATP to be utilized in the muscle.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] The phosphorylation of creatine allows for the storage of readily available phosphate that can be supplied to the muscles.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] The reaction is reversible as well, allowing cellular ATP levels to be maintained during anoxic conditions.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] This process in animals is seen to be coupled with metabolic suppression to allow certain fish, such as goldfish, to survive environmental anoxic conditions for a short period.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Since normal microbial culturing is done in atmospheric air, which contains molecular oxygen, culturing anaerobes requires special techniques.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] The Gas-pak System is an isolated container that achieves an anaerobic environment by the reaction of water with sodium borohydride and sodium bicarbonate tablets, which produce hydrogen gas and carbon dioxide.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Hydrogen then reacts with oxygen gas on a palladium catalyst to produce more water, thereby removing oxygen gas.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] The issue with the Gas-Pak method is that an adverse reaction can occur, leading to bacterial death; therefore, a thioglycolate medium should be used.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] The thioglycolate supplies a medium mimicking that of a dicot plant, thus providing not only an anaerobic environment but all the nutrients needed for the bacteria to multiply.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] On May the 6 2018, a French team evidenced a link between redox and gut anaerobes based on clinical studies of severe acute malnutrition.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] These findings led to the development of an aerobic culture of "anaerobes" by the addition of antioxidants in the culture medium.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Very few multicellular life forms are anaerobic, since only aerobic respiration can provide enough energy for a complex metabolism.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Exceptions include three species of *Loricifera* (< 1 mm in size) and the 10-cell *Henneguya zschokkei*.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] In 2010, three species of anaerobic *Loricifera* were discovered in the hypersaline anoxic L'Atalante basin at the bottom of the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] They lack mitochondria, which contain the oxidative phosphorylation pathway, which in all other animals combines oxygen with glucose to produce metabolic energy; thus, they consume no oxygen.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Instead, these *loricifera* derive their energy from hydrogen, using hydrogenosomes.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Anaerobic respiration and its end products can facilitate symbiosis between anaerobes and aerobes.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] This occurs across taxa, often in compensation for nutritional needs.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Anaerobiosis and symbiosis are found in interactions between ciliates and prokaryotes.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Anaerobic ciliates interact with prokaryotes in an endosymbiotic relationship.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] These relationships are mediated in which the ciliate leaves end products that its prokaryotic symbiont utilizes.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] The ciliate achieves this through fermentative metabolism.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] The rumen of various animals houses this ciliate alongside many other anaerobic bacteria, protozoans, and fungi.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] In specific, methanogenic archaea found in the rumen acts as a symbiont to anaerobic ciliates.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] These anaerobes are useful to those with a rumen due to their ability to break down cellulose, making it bioavailable when otherwise indigestible by animals.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Termites utilize anaerobic bacteria to fix and recapture nitrogen.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Specifically, the termite's hindgut is full of nitrogen-fixing bacteria, whose functions depend on the nitrogen concentration of the diet.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] Acetylene reduction in termites was observed to upregulate in termites with nitrogen-poor diets, meaning that nitrogenase activity rose as the nitrogen content of the termite was reduced.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] One of the functions of termite microbiota is to recapture nitrogen from the termite's uric acid.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] This allows nitrogen conservation from a diet otherwise low in nitrogen.
[src:acetogenesis/anaerobic-bacteria] The hindgut microbiome of different termites has been analyzed, showing 16 different anaerobic species of bacteria, including Clostridia, Enterobacteriaceae, and Gram-positive cocci.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] When consumed in a metabolic process, ATP converts either to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) or to adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Other processes, such as oxidative phosphorylation or substrate-level phosphorylation, regenerate ATP.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP is also a precursor to DNA and RNA, and is used as a coenzyme.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Daily, an average adult human recycles through synthesis and hydrolysis around 50 kilograms of ATP (about 100 moles).
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] From the perspective of biochemistry, ATP is classified as a nucleoside triphosphate, which indicates that it consists of three components: a nitrogenous base (adenine), the sugar ribose, and the triphosphate.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP consists of three parts: a sugar, an amine base, and a phosphate group.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] More specifically, ATP consists of an adenine attached by the #9-nitrogen atom to the 1′ carbon atom of a sugar (ribose), which in turn is attached at the 5' carbon atom of the sugar to a triphosphate group.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] In its many reactions related to metabolism, the adenine and sugar groups remain unchanged, but the triphosphate is converted to di- and monophosphate, giving respectively the derivatives ADP and AMP.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The three phosphoryl groups are labeled as alpha (α), beta (β), and, for the terminal phosphate, gamma (γ).
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] In neutral solution, ionized ATP exists mostly as ATP4−, with a small proportion of ATP3−.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Polyanionic and featuring a potentially chelating polyphosphate group, ATP binds metal cations with high affinity.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The binding constant for Mg2+ is (9554).
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The binding of a divalent cation, almost always magnesium, strongly affects the interaction of ATP with various proteins.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Due to the strength of the ATP-Mg2+ interaction, ATP exists in the cell mostly as a complex with Mg2+ bonded to the phosphate oxygen centers.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] A second magnesium ion is critical for ATP binding in the kinase domain.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The presence of Mg2+ regulates kinase activity.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] It is interesting from an RNA world perspective that ATP can carry a Mg2+ ion which catalyzes RNA polymerization.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Salts of ATP can be isolated as colorless solids.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP is stable in aqueous solutions between pH 6.8 and 7.4 (in the absence of catalysts).
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] At more extreme pH levels, it rapidly hydrolyses to ADP and phosphate.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Living cells maintain the ratio of ATP to ADP at a point ten orders of magnitude from equilibrium, with ATP concentrations fivefold higher than the concentration of ADP.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] In the context of biochemical reactions, the P-O-P bonds are frequently referred to as *high-energy bonds*.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] releases Δ*G*°' = −30.5 kJ/mol (−7.3 kcal/mol) of Gibbs free energy under standard conditions when all metabolite concentrations are 1 mol/L.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] This may differ under physiological conditions if the reactant and products are not exactly in these ionization states.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] At cytoplasmic conditions, where the ADP/ATP ratio is 10 orders of magnitude from equilibrium, the Δ*G* is around −57 kJ/mol.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Along with pH, the free energy change of ATP hydrolysis is also associated with Mg2+ concentration, from ΔG°' = −35.7 kJ/mol at a Mg2+ concentration of zero, to ΔG°' = −31 kJ/mol at [Mg2+] = 5 mM.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Higher concentrations of Mg2+ decrease free energy released in the reaction due to binding of Mg2+ ions to negatively charged oxygen atoms of ATP at pH 7.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] A typical intracellular concentration of ATP is 1–10 μmol per gram of muscle tissue in a variety of eukaryotes.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The dephosphorylation of ATP and rephosphorylation of ADP and AMP occur repeatedly in the course of aerobic metabolism.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP can be produced by a number of distinct cellular processes; the three main pathways in eukaryotes are (1) glycolysis, (2) the citric acid cycle/oxidative phosphorylation, and (3) beta-oxidation.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The overall process of oxidizing glucose to carbon dioxide, the combination of pathways 1 and 2, known as cellular respiration, produces about 30 equivalents of ATP from each molecule of glucose.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP production by a non-photosynthetic aerobic eukaryote occurs mainly in the mitochondria, which comprise nearly 25% of the volume of a typical cell.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] In glycolysis, glucose and glycerol are metabolized to pyruvate.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Glycolysis generates two equivalents of ATP through substrate phosphorylation catalyzed by two enzymes, phosphoglycerate kinase (PGK) and pyruvate kinase.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Two equivalents of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) are also produced, which can be oxidized via the electron transport chain and result in the generation of additional ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The pyruvate generated as an end-product of glycolysis is a substrate for the citric acid cycle.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Glycolysis is viewed as consisting of two phases with five steps each.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] In phase 1, "the preparatory phase", glucose is converted to 2 d-glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (g3p).
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] One ATP is invested in Step 1, and another ATP is invested in Step 3.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Steps 1 and 3 of glycolysis are referred to as "Priming Steps".
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] In Phase 2, two equivalents of g3p are converted to two pyruvates.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Also, in Step 10, two further equivalents of ATP are produced.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] In Steps 7 and 10, ATP is generated from ADP.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] A net of two ATPs is formed in the glycolysis cycle.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The glycolysis pathway is later associated with the Citric Acid Cycle, which produces additional equivalents of ATP.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Glycolysis is regulated allosterically by a number of metabolic compounds.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] For example, hexokinase is directly inhibited by its product, glucose-6-phosphate, and pyruvate kinase is inhibited by ATP itself.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The main control point for the glycolytic pathway is phosphofructokinase 1 (PFK1), which is allosterically inhibited by high concentrations of ATP and activated by high concentrations of AMP.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The inhibition of PFK1 by ATP is unusual since ATP is also a substrate in the reaction catalyzed by PFK1.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The active form of PFK1 enzyme is a tetramer that exists in two conformations, only one of which binds the second substrate fructose-6-phosphate (F6P).
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The PFK1 enzyme has two binding sites for ATP – the active site is accessible in either protein conformation, but ATP binding to the inhibitor site stabilizes the conformation that binds F6P poorly.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] A number of other small molecules can compensate for the ATP-induced shift in equilibrium conformation and reactivate PFK1, including cyclic AMP, ammonium ions, inorganic phosphate, fructose 1,6-bisphosphate and fructose 2,6-bisphosphate.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] In the mitochondrion, pyruvate is oxidized by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex to the acetyl group, which is fully oxidized to carbon dioxide by the citric acid cycle.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] NADH and FADH2 are recycled (to NAD+ and FAD, respectively) by oxidative phosphorylation, generating additional ATP.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The oxidation of NADH results in the synthesis of 2–3 equivalents of ATP, and the oxidation of one FADH2 yields between 1–2 equivalents of ATP.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The majority of cellular ATP is generated by this process.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Although the citric acid cycle itself does not involve molecular oxygen, it is an obligately aerobic process because O2 is used to recycle the NADH and FADH2.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] In the absence of oxygen, the citric acid cycle ceases.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The generation of ATP by the mitochondrion from cytosolic NADH relies on the malate-aspartate shuttle (and to a lesser extent, the glycerol-phosphate shuttle) because the inner mitochondrial membrane is impermeable to NADH and NAD+.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Instead of transferring the generated NADH, a malate dehydrogenase enzyme converts oxaloacetate to malate, which is translocated to the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Another malate dehydrogenase-catalyzed reaction occurs in the opposite direction, producing oxaloacetate and NADH from the newly transported malate and the mitochondrion's interior store of NAD+.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] A transaminase converts the oxaloacetate to aspartate for transport back across the membrane and into the intermembrane space.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] In oxidative phosphorylation, the passage of electrons from NADH and FADH2 through the electron transport chain releases the energy to pump protons out of the mitochondrial matrix and into the intermembrane space.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] This pumping generates a proton motive force that is the net effect of a pH gradient and an electric potential gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Flow of protons down this potential gradient – that is, from the intermembrane space to the matrix – yields ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Most of the ATP synthesized in the mitochondria will be used for cellular processes in the cytosol; thus it must be exported from its site of synthesis in the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP outward movement is favored by the inner mitochondrial membrane's electrochemical potential because the cytosol has a relatively positive charge compared to the relatively negative matrix.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] For every ATP transported out, it costs 1 H+.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Therefore, making and exporting one ATP requires 4H+.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The inner membrane contains an antiporter, the ADP/ATP translocase, which is an integral membrane protein used to exchange newly synthesized ATP in the matrix for ADP in the intermembrane space.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The citric acid cycle is regulated mainly by the availability of key substrates, particularly the ratio of NAD+ to NADH and the concentrations of calcium, inorganic phosphate, ATP, ADP, and AMP.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Citrate – the ion that gives its name to the cycle – is a feedback inhibitor of citrate synthase and also inhibits PFK, providing a direct link between the regulation of the citric acid cycle and glycolysis.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] In the presence of air and various cofactors and enzymes, fatty acids are converted to acetyl-CoA.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Each cycle of beta-oxidation shortens the fatty acid chain by two carbon atoms and produces one equivalent each of acetyl-CoA, NADH, and FADH2.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The acetyl-CoA is metabolized by the citric acid cycle to generate ATP, while the NADH and FADH2 are used by oxidative phosphorylation to generate ATP.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Dozens of ATP equivalents are generated by the beta-oxidation of a single long acyl chain.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] In oxidative phosphorylation, the key control point is the reaction catalyzed by cytochrome c oxidase, which is regulated by the availability of its substrate – the reduced form of cytochrome c.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Thus, a high ratio of [NADH] to [NAD+] or a high ratio of [ADP] [Pi] to [ATP] imply a high amount of reduced cytochrome c and a high level of cytochrome c oxidase activity.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] An additional level of regulation is introduced by the transport rates of ATP and NADH between the mitochondrial matrix and the cytoplasm.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Ketone bodies can be used as fuels, yielding 22 ATP and 2 GTP molecules per acetoacetate molecule when oxidized in the mitochondria.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Ketone bodies are transported from the liver to other tissues, where acetoacetate and *beta*-hydroxybutyrate can be reconverted to acetyl-CoA to produce reducing equivalents (NADH and FADH2), via the citric acid cycle.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Ketone bodies cannot be used as fuel by the liver, because the liver lacks the enzyme β-ketoacyl-CoA transferase, also called thiolase.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Acetoacetate in low concentrations is taken up by the liver and undergoes detoxification through the methylglyoxal pathway which ends with lactate.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Acetoacetate in high concentrations is absorbed by cells other than those in the liver and enters a different pathway via 1,2-propanediol.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Though the pathway follows a different series of steps requiring ATP, 1,2-propanediol can be turned into pyruvate.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Fermentation is the metabolism of organic compounds in the absence of air.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] It involves substrate-level phosphorylation in the absence of a respiratory electron transport chain.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Anaerobic respiration is respiration in the absence of O2.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Prokaryotes can utilize a variety of electron acceptors.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] These include nitrate, sulfate, and carbon dioxide.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] In anaerobic organisms and prokaryotes, different pathways result in ATP.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP is produced in the chloroplasts of green plants in a process similar to oxidative phosphorylation, called photophosphorylation.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP can also be synthesized through several so-called "replenishment" reactions catalyzed by the enzyme families of nucleoside diphosphate kinases (NDKs), which use other nucleoside triphosphates as a high-energy phosphate donor, and the ATP:guanido-phosphotransferase family.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] In plants, ATP is synthesized in the thylakoid membrane of the chloroplast.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The process is called photophosphorylation.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The "machinery" is similar to that in mitochondria except that light energy is used to pump protons across a membrane to produce a proton-motive force.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP synthase then ensues exactly as in oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Some of the ATP produced in the chloroplasts is consumed in the Calvin cycle, which produces triose sugars.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The total quantity of ATP in the human body is about 0.1 mol/L.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The majority of ATP is recycled from ADP by the aforementioned processes.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Thus, at any given time, the total amount of ATP + ADP remains fairly constant.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The energy used by human cells in an adult requires the hydrolysis of 100 to 150 mol/L of ATP daily, which means a human will typically use their body weight worth of ATP over the course of the day.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Each equivalent of ATP is recycled 1000–1500 times during a single day (150 / 0.1 = 1500), at approximately 9×1020 molecules/s.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The conversion of ATP to ADP is the principal mechanism for energy supply in biological processes.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] However, removing a phosphate group from ADP to produce adenosine monophosphate (AMP) also produces extra energy.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP is involved in signal transduction by serving as substrate for kinases, enzymes that transfer phosphate groups.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Kinases are the most common ATP-binding proteins.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] They share a small number of common folds.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Phosphorylation of a protein by a kinase can activate a cascade such as the mitogen-activated protein kinase cascade.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP is also a substrate of adenylate cyclase, most commonly in G protein-coupled receptor signal transduction pathways and is transformed to second messenger, cyclic AMP, which is involved in triggering calcium signals by the release of calcium from intracellular stores.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] This form of signal transduction is particularly important in brain function, although it is involved in the regulation of a multitude of other cellular processes.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP is one of four monomers required in the synthesis of RNA.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The process is promoted by RNA polymerases.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] A similar process occurs in the formation of DNA, except that ATP is first converted to the deoxyribonucleotide dATP.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Like many condensation reactions in nature, DNA replication and DNA transcription also consume ATP.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase enzymes consume ATP in the attachment tRNA to amino acids, forming aminoacyl-tRNA complexes.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Aminoacyl transferase binds AMP-amino acid to tRNA.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The amino acid is coupled to the penultimate nucleotide at the 3′-end of the tRNA (the A in the sequence CCA) via an ester bond (roll over in illustration).
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Transporting chemicals out of a cell against a gradient is often associated with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Transport is mediated by ATP binding cassette transporters.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The human genome encodes 48 ABC transporters, that are used for exporting drugs, lipids, and other compounds.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Cells secrete ATP to communicate with other cells in a process called purinergic signalling.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP serves as a neurotransmitter in many parts of the nervous system, modulates ciliary beating, affects vascular oxygen supply etc.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP is either secreted directly across the cell membrane through channel proteins or is pumped into vesicles which then fuse with the membrane.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Cells detect ATP using the purinergic receptor proteins P2X and P2Y.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP has been shown to be a critically important signalling molecule for microglia - neuron interactions in the adult brain, as well as during brain development.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Furthermore, tissue-injury induced ATP-signalling is a major factor in rapid microglial phenotype changes.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Muscle contractions are regulated by signaling pathways, although different muscle types being regulated by specific pathways and stimuli based on their particular function.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] However, in all muscle types, contraction is performed by the proteins actin and myosin.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] When ATPase hydrolyzes the bound ATP into ADP and inorganic phosphate, myosin is positioned in a way that it can bind to actin.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Myosin bound by ADP and Pi forms cross-bridges with actin and the subsequent release of ADP and Pi releases energy as the power stroke.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The power stroke causes actin filament to slide past the myosin filament, shortening the muscle and causing a contraction.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Another ATP molecule can then bind to myosin, releasing it from actin and allowing this process to repeat.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP has recently been proposed to act as a biological hydrotrope and has been shown to affect proteome-wide solubility.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Acetyl phosphate (AcP), a precursor to ATP, can readily be synthesized at modest yields from thioacetate in pH 7 and 20 °C and pH 8 and 50 °C, although acetyl phosphate is less stable in warmer temperatures and alkaline conditions than in cooler and acidic to neutral conditions.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] It is unable to promote polymerization of ribonucleotides and amino acids and was only capable of phosphorylation of organic compounds.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] It was shown that it can promote aggregation and stabilization of AMP in the presence of Na+, aggregation of nucleotides could promote polymerization above 75 °C in the absence of Na+.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] It is possible that polymerization promoted by AcP could occur at mineral surfaces.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] It was shown that ADP can only be phosphorylated to ATP by AcP and other nucleoside triphosphates were not phosphorylated by AcP.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] This might explain why all lifeforms use ATP to drive biochemical reactions.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Biochemistry laboratories often use *in vitro* studies to explore ATP-dependent molecular processes.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP analogs are also used in X-ray crystallography to determine a protein structure in complex with ATP, often together with other substrates.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Enzyme inhibitors of ATP-dependent enzymes such as kinases are needed to examine the binding sites and transition states involved in ATP-dependent reactions.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Most useful ATP analogs cannot be hydrolyzed as ATP would be; instead, they trap the enzyme in a structure closely related to the ATP-bound state.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Adenosine 5′-(γ-thiotriphosphate) is an extremely common ATP analog in which one of the gamma-phosphate oxygens is replaced by a sulfur atom; this anion is hydrolyzed at a dramatically slower rate than ATP itself and functions as an inhibitor of ATP-dependent processes.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] In crystallographic studies, hydrolysis transition states are modeled by the bound vanadate ion.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Caution is warranted in interpreting the results of experiments using ATP analogs, since some enzymes can hydrolyze them at appreciable rates at high concentration.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP is used intravenously for some heart-related conditions.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] ATP was discovered in 1929 from muscle tissue by Karl Lohmann and Jendrassik and, independently, by Cyrus Fiske and Yellapragada Subba Rao of Harvard Medical School, both teams competing against each other to find an assay for phosphorus.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] It was proposed to be the intermediary between energy-yielding and energy-requiring reactions in cells by Fritz Albert Lipmann in 1941.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] He played a major role in establishing that ATP is the energy currency of a cell.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] It was first synthesized in the laboratory by Alexander Todd in 1948, and he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1957 partly for this work.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The 1978 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Peter Dennis Mitchell for the discovery of the chemiosmotic mechanism of ATP synthesis.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] The 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was divided, one half jointly to Paul D.
[src:acetogenesis/atp-molecule] Walker "for their elucidation of the enzymatic mechanism underlying the synthesis of adenosine triphosphate (ATP)" and the other half to Jens C.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] An **autotroph** is an organism that can convert abiotic sources of energy into energy stored in organic compounds, which can be used by other organisms.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Autotrophs produce complex organic compounds (such as carbohydrates, fats, and proteins) using carbon from simple substances such as carbon dioxide, generally using energy from light or inorganic chemical reactions.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Autotrophs do not need a living source of carbon or energy, and are the producers in a food chain, such as plants on land or algae in water.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Autotrophs can reduce carbon dioxide to make organic compounds for biosynthesis and as stored chemical fuel.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Most autotrophs use water as the reducing agent, but some can use other hydrogen compounds such as hydrogen sulfide.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Autotrophs use a portion of the ATP produced during photosynthesis or the oxidation of chemical compounds to reduce NADP+ to NADPH to form organic compounds.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Primary producers are at the lowest trophic level, and are the reasons why Earth sustains life to this day.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Photoautotrophs convert the energy of light into chemical energy through photosynthesis, ultimately building organic molecules from carbon dioxide, an inorganic carbon source.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Chemolithotrophs produce biomass from the oxidation of inorganic chemical compounds; they are frequently found in hydrothermal vents in the deep ocean and include some archaea and bacteria (unicellular organisms).
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Most chemoautotrophs are lithotrophs, using inorganic electron donors such as hydrogen sulfide, hydrogen gas, elemental sulfur, ammonium, and ferrous oxide as reducing agents; and hydrogen sources for biosynthesis and chemical energy release.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Chemolithoautotrophs are microorganisms that synthesize energy through the oxidation of inorganic compounds.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] They can sustain themselves entirely on atmospheric CO2 and inorganic chemicals without the need for light or organic compounds.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] They enzymatically catalyze redox reactions using mineral substrates to generate ATP energy.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] These substrates primarily include hydrogen, iron, nitrogen, and sulfur.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Its ecological niche is often specialized to extreme environments, including deep marine hydrothermal vents, stratified sediment, and acidic hot springs.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Some organisms rely on organic compounds as a source of carbon, but can use light or inorganic compounds as a source of energy.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] An organism that obtains carbon from organic compounds but obtains energy from light is called a *photoheterotroph*, while an organism that obtains carbon from organic compounds and energy from the oxidation of inorganic compounds is termed a *chemolithoheterotroph*.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Evidence suggests that some fungi may also obtain energy from ionizing radiation: Such radiotrophic fungi were found growing inside a reactor of the Chernobyl nuclear power plant.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] The term *autotroph* was coined by the German botanist Albert Bernhard Frank in 1892.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] It stems from the ancient Greek word τροφή (*trophḗ*), meaning "nourishment" or "food".
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Without primary producers, organisms that are capable of producing energy on their own, the biological systems of Earth would be unable to sustain themselves.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Plants, along with other primary producers, produce the energy that other living beings consume, and the oxygen that they breathe.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] It is thought that the first organisms on Earth were primary producers located on the ocean floor.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Autotrophs are fundamental to the food chains of all ecosystems in the world.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] They take energy from the environment in the form of sunlight or inorganic chemicals and use it to create fuel molecules such as carbohydrates.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] This mechanism is called primary production.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Other organisms, called heterotrophs, take in autotrophs as food to carry out functions necessary for their life.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Thus, heterotrophs – all animals, almost all fungi, and most bacteria and protozoa – depend on autotrophs, or primary producers, for the raw materials and fuel they need.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Heterotrophs obtain energy by breaking down carbohydrates or oxidizing organic molecules (carbohydrates, fats, and proteins) obtained in food.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Carnivorous organisms rely on autotrophs indirectly, as the nutrients obtained from their heterotrophic prey come from autotrophs they have consumed.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Most ecosystems are supported by the autotrophic primary production of plants and cyanobacteria that capture photons initially released by the sun.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Plants can only use a fraction (approximately 1%) of this energy for photosynthesis.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] The process of photosynthesis splits a water molecule (H2O), releasing oxygen (O2) into the atmosphere, and reducing carbon dioxide (CO2) to release hydrogen atoms that fuel the metabolic process of primary production.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Plants convert and store the energy of the photons into the chemical bonds of simple sugars during photosynthesis.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] These plant sugars are polymerized for storage as long-chain carbohydrates, such as starch and cellulose; glucose is also used to make fats and proteins.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] When autotrophs are eaten by heterotrophs, i.e., consumers such as animals, the carbohydrates, fats, and proteins contained in them become energy sources for the heterotrophs.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Proteins can be made using nitrates, sulfates, and phosphates in the soil.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Aquatic algae are a significant contributor to food webs in tropical rivers and streams.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] This is displayed by net primary production, a fundamental ecological process that reflects the amount of carbon that is synthesized within an ecosystem.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] This carbon ultimately becomes available to consumers.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Net primary production displays that the rates of in-stream primary production in tropical regions are at least an order of magnitude greater than in similar temperate systems.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Researchers believe that the first cellular lifeforms were not heterotrophs as they would rely upon autotrophs since organic substrates delivered from space were either too heterogeneous to support microbial growth or too reduced to be fermented.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Instead, they consider that the first cells were autotrophs.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] These autotrophs might have been thermophilic and anaerobic chemolithoautotrophs that lived at deep sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] This view is supported by phylogenetic evidence – the physiology and habitat of the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) is inferred to have also been a thermophilic anaerobe with a Wood-Ljungdahl pathway, its biochemistry was replete with FeS clusters and radical reaction mechanisms.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] The high concentration of K+ present within the cytosol of most life forms suggests that early cellular life had Na+/H+ antiporters or possibly symporters.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Autotrophs possibly evolved into heterotrophs when they were at low H2 partial pressures where the first form of heterotrophy were likely amino acid and clostridial type purine fermentations.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] It has been suggested that photosynthesis emerged in the presence of faint near-infrared light emitted by hydrothermal vents.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] The first photochemically active pigments are then thought to be Zn-tetrapyrroles.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] The first autotrophic organisms likely evolved early in the Archean but proliferated across Earth's Great Oxidation Event with an increase to the rate of oxygenic photosynthesis by cyanobacteria.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Photoautotrophs evolved from heterotrophic bacteria by developing photosynthesis.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] The earliest photosynthetic bacteria used hydrogen sulfide.
[src:acetogenesis/autotroph] Due to the scarcity of hydrogen sulfide, some photosynthetic bacteria evolved to use water in photosynthesis, leading to cyanobacteria.
